?</gtr:impact><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Public/other audiences</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:url>https://gsachurchproject.wordpress.com/</gtr:url><gtr:year>2012</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>English Heritage Listing of St Raphael, Stalybridge</gtr:description><gtr:form>Participation in an activity, workshop or similar</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>National</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>DB51E074-CAC5-42A4-89D3-FB8A0515AC57</gtr:id><gtr:impact>The Roman Catholic church of St Raphael, Stalybridge (designed by Massey &amp;amp; Massey, 1960-63) was closed in the summer of 2011 and its owners, the Diocese of Shrewsbury, applied for demolition. It then became the subject of a listing campaign by the Manchester Modernist Society, who contacted Robert Proctor, the PI grant-holder, for advice. We responded with a detailed assessment of the building's significance. The case was taken up by the Twentieth Century Society, who recommended the building for listing; it was then listed by English Heritage in December 2011 at Grade II. English Heritage's report on its listing decision incorporated much of the assessment sent by us. The Manchester Modernist Society sent out press releases which brought mention of the case in the local and national press.

