http://menmedia.co.uk/manchestereveningnews/news/s/1469020_unholy-row-over-plan-to-demolish-modern-gem-stalybridge-church 

http://www.guardian.co.uk/artanddesign/2011/dec/23/constructive-criticism-week-in-architecture</gtr:impact><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Policymakers/parliamentarians</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:url>http://menmedia.co.uk/manchestereveningnews/news/s/1469020_unholy-row-over-plan-to-demolish-modern-gem-stalybridge-church</gtr:url><gtr:year>2011</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Exhibition, 'Churches in the Modern World: Roman Catholic Church Architecture in Britain, 1955-75'</gtr:description><gtr:form>A talk or presentation</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>National</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>D141D69C-885E-4C70-9281-1D1E13553944</gtr:id><gtr:impact>This exhibition was a major part of the public impact aspect of the project. It brought together nine case study buildings from the research, presented through new and archival photography, new survey drawings, and quotations from original documents of the period. The aim was to explain modern Roman Catholic church architecture to a general audience to raise greater awareness of its historical importance. The exhibition was designed by Collective Architecture in Glasgow, with the aim of allowing it to be shown in non-gallery spaces such as churches. In its showing in Glasgow at the Lighthouse architecture centre it was accompanied with projections showing Scottish churches of the period. The exhibition was organised according to three themes: Tradition and Modernity; Devotion and Liturgy; and Church and City. It received limited press interest but news was circulated to architects and parish churches in each area and each show drew a significant audience from both sectors. The first showings of the exhibition were timed to coincide with Doors Open Days in Glasgow and Heritage Open Days in Liverpool to maximise audiences. The open nature of most venues precluded collecting visitor figures, but figures were obtained from the Lighthouse and showed over 6,000 visits.

The exhibition was initially shown in two venues in parallel. One version was displayed at the Lighthouse centre for architecture and design in Glasgow. Another was displayed in a side chapel at Liverpool Metropolitan Cathedral. Both were timed to coincid</gtr:impact><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Public/other audiences</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:url>https://gsachurchproject.wordpress.com/category/exhibition/</gtr:url><gtr:year>2012</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>'Networks of Reform in Church Architecture: Before and After Vatican II', at Historic Churches Committees Conference, Salisbury, 17 May 2012</gtr:description><gtr:form>A talk or presentation</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>National</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>93073521-B6C0-4C07-B47C-118CD6DD8EC0</gtr:id><gtr:impact>This was essentially a 30-minute conference paper about an aspect of the research project, given at the annual conference of the Roman Catholic diocesan Historic Churches Committees, organised by the Patrimony Committee of the hierarchy of England and Wales. It was one of three talks presented at this conference, the others being on Pugin and on recent church reordering. The event was attended by church and conservation architects, architectural historians including staff at English Heritage and architectural history consultants, senior clergy involved in church heritage, diocesan surveyors and other staff. 



The talk attempted to explain the mechanisms of reform, showing how networks of architects and clergy had built up the case for reform in church architecture and liturgy together for a decade before the Second Vatican Council. Key case study buildings and people were used as ways of drawing together a narrative of significant buildings, publications and formative events that matured in the church architecture that followed Vatican II.

-</gtr:impact><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Professional Practitioners</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:year>2012</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput></gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>The book, Building the Modern Church, has become a key work for surveys and investigation of post-war church heritage in Britain. It has been used by the Architectural History Practice, for example, who have been commissioned by Historic England to undertake diocese-by-diocese surveys of Roman Catholic church properties to assess their heritage significance. It has also been used by the Twentieth Century Society to augment their own documentation of British church architecture (including a new online database), and to investigate potential applications for listing. In Manchester and London, bus tours were organised by heritage groups (Manchester Modernist Society, Twentieth Century Society) of local modern churches, partly following and inspired by the book. The book has been sold not just to academic libraries but also through the Twentieth Century Society (which reviewed it in its magazine), to heritage professionals and architects as well as the general public interested in modern architecture. New interest in this topic has led to renewed conservation efforts. For example, at the church of St Thomas More in Sheldon, recently listed, the parishioners were awarded a Heritage Lottery Fund grant for repair and conservation work, and the PI was invited to talk to parishioners and the conservation architect about the building, raising greater appreciation for its design qualities. Publication work continues, for example with a recent commission received by the PI to research and write a book chapter on the stained glass artist Charles Norris, a monk of Buckfast Abbey, to be published in a book on the Abbey's art and architecture in 2017 for a mainstream publisher, both for general sale but also for the Abbey itself to sell and distribute to supporters.</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2014</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>D61F56EC-40FC-45CA-92FC-541AC48869ED</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Cultural</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:sector>Culture, Heritage, Museums and Collections</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>Roman Catholic church architecture of the period 1955 to 1975 has rarely been studied in any depth, and the AHRC grant for this project enabled a consolidation of the PI Robert Proctor's research to date and extension through new detailed research on specific case study buildings. New findings included, for example:



- Correspondence about a new church showing a crisis over its perceived traditionalism, motivated by parishioners' complaints;

- A parish council's detailed preparations for briefing an architect and statements about their negotiations with the architect;

- Architects' development sketches for an important church with an innovative plan;

- Photographs of a church reputed for its liturgical advances showing it in use for the liturgy shortly after its construction, confirming suspicions that liturgical practices had not yet advanced as far as the building suggested;

- Discovery of two little-known buildings by a significant church architect of the period;

- Records of decisions about churches amongst New Town planners, showing how churches were allocated sites in new developments.

- Discovery and acquisition of a modest archive of a highly productive architectural practice specialising in churches, which will eventually be deposited in a publicly accessible repository.



These and other findings have given a complex historical picture of the movement from traditional to modern church architecture and of the development of liturgical innovation in relation to church planning; and also further information on the relationships of new churches to changes in city contexts and urban planning.



Major outputs so far have included:



- A conference paper for the European Architectural History Network annual conference;

- A travelling exhibition that visited numerous churches and other venues, many of them significant buildings of the period, including Liverpool Metropolitan Cathedral.


